<TEXT>
young children with ironpoor diets may risk 
problems in mental and physical performance that will continue as 
they enter school a researcher says 
new research findings underline the importance of preventing iron 
deficiencies from birth said betsy lozoff of the case western 
reserve university school of medicine in cleveland 
a study of 191 outwardly healthy oneyearolds in costa rica 
found that those with anemia caused by iron deficiency scored lower 
than other children in mental and physical performance 
preliminary results of a followup study suggest the score 
deficits persisted in those children through age 5 even though the 
anemia had long since been corrected lozoff said thursday 
the children scored within normal ranges for mental and physical 
abilities but the deficits might be enough to affect performance in 
school lozoff said 
speaking at a symposium on nutrition children and health 
sponsored by the new york academy of medicine and the new york state 
department of health she cautioned that the study does not prove 
iron deficiencies cause the poor scores 
myron winick a professor of nutrition and pediatrics at the 
columbia university college of physicians and surgeons in new york 
agreed with that caution perhaps other circumstances that tend to 
occur in homes of children with iron deficiencies are really 
responsible he said 
in any case iron deficiencies in young children can be prevented 
by breast feeding using ironfortified formula and cereal and 
keeping iron in mind when solid foods are introduced lozoff said 
among american children such steps have cut the prevalence of 
irondeficiency anemia from about 25 percent of infants to about 3 
percent to 8 percent lozoff said 
in the costa rican study anemic oneyearolds showed deficits in 
both mental measures and in performance on such tasks as walking by 
themselves climbing stairs and walking along a board 
results of efforts to eliminate such deficits by correcting the 
anemia have been discouraging raising the question of whether the 
iron deficiency is truly to blame lozoff said 
researchers have also found that if very young rats are given too 
little iron a deficiency of the mineral in their brains will 
persist into adulthood even if the ironpoor diet is corrected in 
later life she said 
such studies have not been done in humans because they require 
removing brain tissue lozoff said 
</TEXT>
