<TEXT>
the american system of handling grain exports 
has so many problems with quality control that the united states 
could lose its leading role in the world market says a report 
requested by congress 
the report released thursday by the office of technology 
assessment said us policy on grain lacks even have one definition 
of quality 
in grain the word quality has a variety of meanings being 
free of foreign material not cracked or spoiled or having the 
proper characteristic for a particular use the report said 
the problems with american grain have led to an increase in 
foreign complaints the report said 
in the 1970s onethird of the worlds countries supplied grain 
to twothirds of the world today the reverse is true the report 
said this highly competitive environment has made foreign buyers 
increasingly sensitive about the quality of grain they import 
the report was prepared at the request of the house committee on 
agriculture and the joint economic committee 
at a news conference on the report sen kent conrad dnd 
said he did not agree with everything it in but that it was 
important in determining how the united states can improve its 
competitive edge 
its a starting point for further debate he said 
both he and sens thomas daschle dnd and charles grassley 
riowa mentioned that they were troubled by reports of cement chips 
in us grain that had been shipped to foreign ports 
my farmers tell me their grain is clean when it is brought to 
the elevator said daschle 
conrad said the secretary of agriculture has been asked to 
investigate further 
michael phillips who headed the ota study said the problem is 
with the whole system of marketing grain to foreign countries 
compared with other grainexporting countries the us system is 
more complex phillips said 
he said other countries address the quality problems as part of 
an integrated agricultural policy with more controls at the first 
point of sale 
most other exporters clean grain at the first point of receipt 
while no economic incentive to do so exists in the united states he 
said 
he also said foreign buyers complain about the way the united 
states blends a wide range of different quality grains in an attempt 
to create a uniform product but this causes differences in 
shipments 
rep dan glickman dkan said enhancing grain quality must 
begin with the design of commodity programs research at 
universities and seed breeders on new grain varieties and the 
standardization of testing procedures 
phillips said however the united states still has many 
advantages over its biggest competitors argentina brazil canada 
and australia 
