<TEXT>
a federal appeals court has cleared the way 
for native alaskans to sue the government in their bid to stop the 
offshore oil drilling they contend is destroying traditional hunting 
grounds 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals on thursday ruled that the 
aboriginal rights the natives held in the submerged land part 
of the bering sea were not destroyed by the 1971 alaska native 
claims settlement act which provided money to resolve all natives 
prestatehood claims of rights in alaska land 
the 30 ruling means several hundred natives from the villages of 
gambell and stebbins can try to prove that drilling in the federally 
approved lease sale 57 made up of 24 million acres off norton 
sound off alaskas western coast would hurt their ability to fish 
and hunt for survival needs 
however the judges left open the question of whether a 1953 
federal law that authorized offshore oil and gas leases had affected 
the natives offshore claims that issue was returned to a lower 
court 
the natives have sued the interior department contending that 
its sale of leases violated their legal rights of subsistence 
hunting and fishing on undersea federal land between alaskas 
threemile offshore boundary and the 200mile federal limit 
carol daniel of alaska legal services corp said the natives have 
hunted and fished on the ice since time immemorial building 
roads and making camps on the ice several miles offshore to catch 
fish walrus and whales 
the drilling is so dangerous to resources and my clients are so 
dependent on the resources said daniel attorney for the 
villagers they dont have access to the same grocery stores most 
people do the sea is their market 
e edward bruce attorney for five oil companies that hold leases 
in the area said no decision has been made on whether to appeal the 
ruling 
he said oil companies paid over 300 million for leases in march 
1983 and completed exploratory drilling several years ago but had 
not done any drilling for oil production 
bruce said he had not been told the results of the exploratory 
drilling but he observed that the results were not sufficiently 
promising to cause further exploratory drilling in the area 
the federal government in other cases has recognized native 
americans aboriginal rights to follow ageold practices of hunting 
and fishing for necessities on government land 
