president bush today announced he will propose 
legislation to halt exports of hazardous waste unless there is an 
agreement that the receiving country will handle the material in an 
approved safe manner 
the presidents proposal would involve waste that us industry 
ships for disposal in other countries concerns have been raised by 
environmentalists that some countries particularly in the 
developing world do not regulate disposal and handling of such 
wastes in an environmentally safe manner 
bush in remarks at the swearingin cermony for health and human 
services secretary louis sullivan said he would send legislation to 
congress to empower the united states to block exports by us 
companies unless safety can be ensured through a bilateral pact 
the legislation will give the us government the authority to 
ban all exports of hazardous waste except where we have an agreement 
with the receivng country providing for the safe handling and 
management of those wastes he said 
were determined to work with other concerned governments to 
exercise wide stewardship over our environment particularly where 
matters of health are concerned bush said 
the legislation bush proposes would affect any us companies 
that export hazardous waste rather than dispose of it in the 
approved domestic sites said linda fisher assistant environemental 
protection agency director for policy 
she said most us exports go to canda and mexico where other 
companies that deal in waste receive it in mexico some handlers 
use the waste in recycling efforts she said 
most of the countries that have caused concern are third world 
nations she said 
under current law the united states has to notify another 
country that hazardous waste is being shipped to them we dont have 
any mechanism to make sure it is being handled properly in other 
country she said 
bushs proposed bill would ensure that companies only ship to 
countries that have a bilateral agreement with the united states to 
make sure it is handled in a manner that does not endanger health 
and the environment 
