<TEXT>
european interior ministers agreed friday 
on the need to create an intelligence exchange service to combat 
problems arising from the planned elimination in four years of 
borders in the 12nation trade bloc 
the officials did not discuss the scope or future evolution of 
the service said spanish interior minister jose luis corcuera 
he said his fellow ministers asked spain to prepare a document 
outlining the service in time for a may 1213 meeting of the trevi 
group of interior ministers created in 1976 to coordinate 
antiterrorist operations in the european economic community 
interiors ministers from greece spain and france will review the 
document before the may meeting 
british home secretary douglas hurd said earlier that he did not 
believe an eec police force would be established in the forseeable 
future 
what will emerge is a greater cooperation between police 
forces hurd said 
corcuera admitted there was caution on the part of several 
countries about the scope of the service but added agreement on its 
importance was a step forward in the fight against new eec security 
problems 
the least important thing is what it might become in the 
future he said we have to assure that the elimination of 
internal borders is neither good for criminals nor generates greater 
insecurity for citizens 
corcuera said the ministers differed over what types of border 
controls should exist among eec countries after dec 31 1992 when 
the single european act is set to take effect eliminating barriers 
to the movement of capital goods and labor within the trading bloc 
spain advocates the elimination of all controls between eec 
countries while other countries including britain favor border 
checks for noneec nationals a move that would effectively leave 
the current system intact 
problems in a borderfree eec could include increased mobility 
for terrorists transnational currency frauds and the difficulty of 
hot pursuit of criminals across national borders corcuera said 
in addition to the intelligence exchange service and internal 
borders corcuera said the ministers discussed the problems of 
defining crimes common to all eec countries 
these are problems that can affect the legislative domain and 
sovereignty of some countries he said adding that progress was 
very difficult 
spain holds the sixmonth rotating presidency of the eec 
</TEXT>
