<TEXT>
the soviet union has reduced the size of its 
pacific battle fleet by 40 ships since 1984 as a unilateral step to 
move soviet forces to a more defensive posture a senior soviet 
military analyst told the house armed services committee on friday 
the appearance of andrei a kokoshin deputy director of the 
institute of the usa and canada represented only the second time a 
representative of the soviet government has appeared before a 
committee of congress chairman les aspin dwis said it was the 
first of a series 
kokoshin testifying against the backdrop of massed display of 
us military banners topped with clusters of battle streamers gave 
details of other unilateral soviet military reductions ordered by 
president mikhail s gorbachev declaring that moscow would be 
gratified if similar reductions were ordered by western military 
forces in return 
he said the reduction of military forces in eastern europe 
announced by gorbachev in a speech before the united nations general 
assembly last december will be conducted in two phases and will be 
completed by the end of next year 
the soviet leadership also has determined not to modernize 
shortrange tactical nuclear weapons in eastern europe and will 
destroy the existing soviet stockpile of chemical weapons kokoshin 
said he did not say whether the soviets have stopped production of 
such weapons 
kokoshin said that in addition to removing 40 ships from the 
pacific fleet between 1984 and 1988 his government has changed the 
nature of fleet maneuvers keeping exercises closer to soviet shores 
to protect assets on the coastline 
a wellplaced congressional source said the committee was briefed 
by representatives of the central intelligence agency earlier this 
week and given information not inconsistent with the details of 
kokoshins testimony on soviet unilateral reductions 
the agency agrees said the source who asked not to be 
identified by name 
kokoshin said the cuts ordered by gorbachev in soviet and warsaw 
pact forces will be made in two stages 
this year he said two tank divisions and all their equipment 
will be pulled out of east germany 
in 1990 he added an additional two tank divisions and assault 
landing brigade will be withdrawn 
two other tank divisions will be withdrawn one from 
czechoslovakia and one from hungary on a time schedule to be 
announced the soviet witness said 
additionally remaining motor rifle divisions will have 40 
percent fewer tanks than at present and remaining tank divisions 
will have 20 percent fewer he said 
overall 10000 tanks are to be removed 5000 to be crushed and 
destroyed and 5000 to be refitted for training purposes or 
converted to civilian purposes such as removing train wrecks he 
said 
he said the remaining soviet units in eastern europe will be 
provided with additional antitank and shortrange antiaircraft 
weapons and mining equipment together with engineering forces for 
defensive purposes 
twentyfour missile launchers also will be removed from east 
germany he said 
kokoshin said senior soviet military commanders especially in 
the red army initially opposed the reductions but were persuaded by 
wellprepared analytical studies 
military establishments tend to be pretty conservative he 
said but they started catching up and they are catching up pretty 
quickly 
he said the nuclear parity his country has reached with the 
united states was a factor in convincing soviet commanders that 
reductions in western europe were an acceptable risk 
with a frankness that would have been highly unlikely in an 
earlier era of soviet history especially in such a setting 
kokoshin said excessive military spending drained the soviet 
economy contributed to a lower living standard than that in the 
west and prevented the kremlin from addressing such pressing issues 
as fighting damage to the environment 
we spent excessively he said there is a lot of fatwe 
frightened the western side by doing a little more than we needed 
now is the time to go in the other direction 
kokoshin said soviet officials initially regarded former 
president reagans strategic defense initiative as an american 
attempt to achieve nuclear superiority and waged an excessive 
propaganda war against it 
it was less the fault of the specialists than it was of the 
propaganda machine the media people he said 
now we are more confident about our capability to cope with 
this threat he said ticking off a list of countermeasures such 
as the massive use of decoys the deployment of many more missiles 
and the use of radio and electronic warfare 
but he said that even though soviet officials believe they can 
cope with a fully deployed american sdi system the strategic 
balance in such an event would be less stable than it is now 
</TEXT>
