<TEXT>
kermit beahan the bombardier who dropped the 
atomic bomb on nagasaki japan on aug 9 1945 that killed about 
70000 people has died at the age of 70 after suffering cardiac 
arrest 
beahan died thursday a day after he underwent prostate surgery 
in a hospital in nassau bay near his home in suburban clear lake 
the bomb beahan released was the last atom bomb dropped on human 
beings and in 1985 the 40th anniversay of the bombing he said he 
hoped to retain that dubious distinction 
he said he would never apologize for his deed that was followed 
by the japanese surrender adding that 25 japanese sought him out a 
few years ago and told him the bombing was the best way out of a 
hell of a mess 
beahan became a bombardier in the army air corps after washing 
out as a pilot candidate 
he took part in 40 missions over europe including the first b17 
raids his b17 unit was commanded by paul w tibbets who later 
assembled the team that dropped two atom bombs on japan 
in addition to dropping the second atomic bomb beahan was aboard 
a plane that escorted the enola gay tibbets plane that dropped the 
first bomb on hiroshima on aug 6 1945 
beahan recalled the nagasaki bombing in an interview with the 
houston chronicle 
i saw a mushroom cloud bubbling and flashing orange red and 
green he said it looked like a picture of hell the ground 
itself was covered by a rolling black smoke i was told the area 
would be destroyed but i didnt know the meaning of an atomic 
bomb 
beahan retired from the air force as a lieutenant colonel in 1963 
and worked for brown amp root inc a houstonbased engineering and 
construction firm as a technical writer until he retired in 1985 
survivors include his wife teresa a daughter two sons and a 
brother 
graveside services were scheduled for monday 
