<TEXT>
the government is losing millions of dollars on 
federal land sales because it hasnt modernized a 115yearold law 
that allows real estate speculators to buy federal property at less 
than bargainbasement rates says a new general accounting office 
report 
rep nick rahall dwva said loopholes in the mining law of 
1872 have enabled developers to purchase federal land near gambling 
casinos and ski resorts at fire sale prices 
rahall chairman of the house subcommittee on mining said he 
plans to offer legislation to modernize the law so that it will do 
what it is supposed to do promote mineral exploration 
the gao report released this week and requested by rahall shows 
that the government received less that 4500 for land estimated to 
be worth up to 48 million 
the report also said the gao reviewed 12 pending applications for 
public land appraised at about 47 million that would be sold for 
only 16000 
the intent of the mining law is to facilitate mineral 
extraction not to serve as a vehicle for land speculation and 
profiteering at the publics expense said rahall 
under the law enacted when ulysses s grant was president 
claims to valuable deposits of minerals such as gold and silver on 
public lands could be patented for 250 an acre 
the patent transfers title to the land from the federal 
government to the private claim holder about 32 million acres of 
public land have been sold in this way the gao report said 
land covered by the act and near resort areas expanding 
communities and tourist attractions has been particularly 
attractive to developers who have no plans for mining 
interior secretary manuel lujan said wednesday he believes the 
law should be changed to bring the prices for the land into line 
with modern times he said that as long as the law mandates 250 an 
acre thats what the interior department must use as the cost 
these federal lands are owned by all of the people and should 
be held as a public trust said rahall we are being done a 
grave injustice by these giveaways and this law must be changed 
land covered by the mining law is in 12 states montana wyoming 
colorado new mexico arizona nevada utah idaho washington 
oregon california and alaska 
the gao gave several examples of valuable land going for cheap 
prices 
a 160acre claim near the keystone colo ski resort that was 
sold for 400 by the government in 1983 under the mining act was 
never mined the buyer offered 44 acres of the claim for sale last 
year at 484000 
an application was filed in 1987 for 1280 acres near lake mead 
within three miles of nine gambling casinos in laughlin nev if 
patented at the 250 an acre rate the land will produce 3200 for 
the government while according to a local real estate agent 
private interests could get between 256 million and 32 million 
