<TEXT>
the washington state apple industry friday 
reported an increase in sales indicating their product is popular 
despite concerns over use of a possibly hazardous chemical 
but officials for the natural resources defense council whose 
report last week said there was an increased risk of cancer for 
children who eat apples treated with alar a chemical which 
regulates the fruits growth questioned the sales figures 
i dont think you can believe those figures said janet 
hathaway an nrdc attorney and coauthor of the report intolerable 
risk pesticides in our childrens food 
ms hathaway said virtually every parent she has talked to 
recently is looking for organic sources of apples and that she has 
received phone calls from growers saying they cannot sell 
alartreated apples 
the washington apple industry which supplies about twothirds of 
the nations supermarket apples this time of year reported shipping 
a record 156 million 42pound boxes between march 2 and march 9 
said bill dewitt of the wenatchee valley traffic association 
that was up from 151 million boxes the week before and 14 
million boxes for the same period last year dewitt said 
its indicating to us that people still like apples and theyre 
still buying them said dewitt manager of the industry trade 
group that compiles shipment figures from warehouses in the state 
the apple market has not suffered nearly what we thought when 
the bad publicity came out dewitt said in a telephone interview 
alar trade name for the chemical daminozide is sprayed on apple 
trees to help the apples stay on longer improving color and 
crispness and giving farmers more time to harvest the environmental 
protection agency has said it intends to ban alar by 1990 based on 
preliminary cancer tests on mice and rats but it is still legal to 
use 
last weeks nrdc report drew widespread attention and resulted in 
some cancelled shipments new york schools stopped selling apples in 
cafeterias and a taiwan exporter cancelled an order for 5000 boxes 
of washington apples 
but the nations 20000 growers have responded with a 1 million 
public relations campaign pointing out that only a small portion of 
the crop is treated with alar and that eating apples is still safe 
the washington apple commission has said about 5 percent of the 
crop is treated with alar the nrdc disputes that putting the 
figure at over 10 percent ms hathaway said 
the shipment figures show apples that are purchased by all 
outofstate retailers exporters and other apple users dewitt said 
theyre buying them because they know they can sell them 
dewitt said 
many major retail chains and apple juice processors accept only 
alarfree apples and to the best of my knowledge thats exactly 
what we are shipping dewitt said 
</TEXT>
