the jury in the fawaz younis sky piracy trial 
began deliberations friday under instructions from the judge that 
undercut the defendants argument that he was acting under militia 
orders when he hijacked a plane in beirut 
orders to hijack a plane are illegal orders us 
district judge aubrey e robinson jr told jurors obedience to 
illegal orders is no defense 
the judge said that only if younis did not know that hijacking 
was illegal should he be acquitted 
the jury deliberated for about for hours deliberations will 
resume monday 
younis was on the stand for two days in the nineday trial 
testifying that the military commander of lebanons amal militia 
aqil hamiyya ordered him to lead four other heavily armed men in 
the hijacking of royal jordanian airlines flight 402 on june 11 
1985 
under crossexamination younis has testified that he knew that 
hijacking was illegal in peacetime and that amal was not at war 
with royal jordanian airlines the government of jordan the two 
americans aboard the aircraft or any of the other 70 passengers and 
crew members 
he did not attempt to refute testimony by five eyewitnesses who 
pointed him out in the courtroom as the leader in the hijacking 
defense attorney frank d carter sought to persuade the jury that 
younis acted as he did because he was a victim of the civil war that 
has engulfed lebanon since 1975 
younis now 30 was arrested on sept 13 1987 by members of the 
fbi hostage rescue team who working closely with the us military 
and intelligence agencies lured him aboard a yacht in international 
waters in the mediterranean sea 
the case is viewed as a test of a 1984 longarm statute that 
asserts us jurisdiction over cases involving american hostages 
taken abroad 
the counts against younis and the maximum possible sentences for 
each are hostage taking life in prison aircraft piracy 20 
years performing acts of violence against individuals 20 years 
destruction of a civilian aircraft 20 years carrying aboard an 
aircraft devices likely to endanger its safety 20 years and 
conspiracy to commit a hijacking five years 
