<TEXT>
emergency medical care at public hospitals is 
suffering due to increases in aids patients drug overdose cases and 
elderly patients as well as cuts in government funding hospital 
administrators said friday 
the problem is so severe that patients requiring emergency 
treatment face up to a threeday wait for hospital beds in the new 
york city area and waits of up to 18 hours in los angeles and 12 
hours in miami said larry s gage president of the national 
association of public hospitals 
gage said hospitals in boston chicago st louis washington 
dc and even memphis tenn are severely strained doctors are 
facing a challenge to their hippocratic oath to give patients bad 
treatment in some cases or no treatment at all he said 
we are rationing health care for the poor in a necessary 
aggressive way he said 
gage was one of more than a dozen speakers at an emergency 
conference friday on indigent care sponsored by the public hospitals 
association the association serves 85 public and nonprofit 
hospitals 
we know what to do we just dont have the resources said 
arthur kellerman medical director of the emergency department at 
regional medical center in memphis we are being put in the 
position of having to give inadequate care to our patients we have 
situations where we have one doctor two nurses and 30 patients in 
the emergency room 
kellerman said a crisis has occurred in the past two years 
because hospitals have reduced total beds under pressure from the 
federal and state governments medicare funding has been cut and 
more and more people are without adequate hospital insurance 
in addition many hospitals have instituted costcontainment 
programs at government urging at a time when victims of acquired 
immune deficiency syndrome are increasing 
hospitals also are seeing more drug overdoses as a result of 
rising crack cocaine use and more elderly are being sent to 
hospitals rather than nursing homes he said 
in denver the problem was so severe thursday night that five of 
nine hospitals were on ambulance diversion not accepting any 
new emergency patients because there were no critical care beds 
available said kellerman 
charity hospital in new orleans lost its certification in part 
because of a staffing shortage as a result of budget cuts he said 
kellerman said some hospitals have worsened the situation by 
phasing out their emergency rooms 
in los angeles for example most central public hospitals have 
closed their emergency rooms and people have to travel 30 minutes 
to a suburban hospital for treatment he said besides endangering 
patients lives this also hurts the community by taking ambulances 
out of service for long periods of time he said 
gage who testified earlier this month before congress on the 
issue said the association is asking congress to change funding 
procedures for hospitals 
the organization wants to put less emphasis on university 
hospitals and more on public hospitals to change medicaid funding 
and to consider some form of national health insurance 
