<TEXT>
food shortages in several vietnamese 
provinces have forced some peasants to eat roots and sell farming 
utensils to buy grain but the government can provide only limited 
aid according to an official 
the shortages resulted from severe weather conditions that 
destroyed crops last year and are expected to last until the next 
harvest in may and june 
agriculture minister nguyen cong tan said that even in normal 
conditions about 10 percent of vietnams peasant families experience 
food shortages annually including those in the mekong river delta 
in the south that is the countrys most productive area 
tans comments came in an interview the official vietnamese army 
newspaper quan doi nhan dan published last month a translation was 
seen friday in bangkok 
tan reported shortages in the northern and central provinces of 
lang son thanh hoa nghe tinh binh tri tien quang namdanang and 
gia laicong tum and in areas east of nam bo and the mekong river 
delta in the south vietnamese radio reported earlier this month 
that hundreds of thousands of rural families in nghe tinh where 
floods had hit have run out of food grain 
tan said 90 percent of the peasants in the ky anh district of 
nghe tinh were short of food and some had to sell their utensils 
and private property to buy grain others had to dig roots in the 
forest to eat 
he said ky anh has lost five consecutive crops since 1986 and its 
per capita output of grain was only about 70 pounds last year 
vietnamese officials said total national grain production was 19 
million metric tons last year an increase over the previous year 
but the country is still losing the struggle to feed a fastgrowing 
population of more than 63 million 
</TEXT>
