<TEXT>
the government trying to head off an 
increasingly severe urban smog problem this summer ordered tougher 
hydrocarbon emission standards for gasoline friday but the federal 
action is not as tough as some states would like 
the environmental protection agency announced that for the first 
time gasoline will have to meet nationwide volatility levels these 
levels which are controlled during the blending process determine 
how easily gasoline evaporates and in turn how much hydrocarbon 
pollutants get into the air 
hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides are key ingredient of ozone and 
urban smog 
under the epa requirements gasoline volatility may be no greater 
than 105 pounds per inch in most parts of the country this summer 
in some states especially during the hottest months the standard 
is somewhat tougher 
the epa action is the first time the federal government has told 
the petroleum industry it had to curb volatility to a specific level 
on nationwide basis there have been local limits in southern 
california since the early 1970s 
the epa estimated the federal requirement which sets a 105 psi 
gasoline volatility level or lower in every state would mean a 13 
percent reduction of hydrocarbon emissions into the air gasoline 
volatility generally has been at at a level of 115 psi 
but the epa said that level causes a release of gasoline vapors 
beyond the capacity of existing vehicleemission controls to 
handle as a result vapors are released into the air from auto fuel 
systems as well as while gasoline is transferred from one storage 
area to another or while vehicles are being fueled officials said 
most of our major urban areas suffer from unhealthful summer 
smog levels said epa administrator william k reilly in a 
statement the standards set today will help reduce this harmful 
pollutant 
the country had the worst urban smog problem in recent years last 
summer with nationwide ozone levels higher than anytime in this 
decade and 14 percent greater than the year before federal maximum 
ozone levels were exceeded 60 percent more often last summer than in 
1983 the worst previous year 
but a group of northeastern states have pushed for even tougher 
restrictions and officials in those states have expressed concerns 
that their state requirements which would limit gasoline 
volatility to 9 psi this summer might be scuttled by the federal 
regulation 
by law federal emission rules normally would preempt local 
requirements unless specific waivers are provided epa officials 
said the epa said last month it plans to grant a waiver to 
massachusetts but the agency has not acted on waiver requests from 
the other six states states 
the tougher gasoline volatility standards enacted for this summer 
are to go into effect may 1 in massachusetts rhode island 
connecticut new york new jersey vermont and maine unless 
preempted by the federal regulation 
the tougher state standards have been strongly opposed by the 
petroleum industry the american petroleum institute has filed suit 
in new york seeking to prevent that states tougher restrictions 
from going into effect it argues the state requirements which 
establish a maximum 9 psi volatility level for gasoline sold between 
may 1 and sept 15 could cause driving problems and problems in 
gasoline distribution 
but supporters of the more stringent requirements deny that the 
lower volatility levels adversely affect gasoline performance they 
maintain the oil companies opposition to the tighter standards stem 
from the fact the gasoline with the lower volatility is more 
expensive to produce 
the northeast is faced with a sever ozone problem in the 
summer months we have two choices we can either reduce emissions 
that contribute to ozone formation or we can continue to ask people 
to restrict their activity during ozone episodes said michael 
bradley executive director of a coalition of state enviornmental 
officials formed to implement the tougher requirements in the seven 
northeastern states 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

