institute said in an interview that 255 residents of two villages 
on the slopes of the pacaya volcano were forced to evacuate their 
homes because of lava flows 
pacaya 16 miles south of the capital started spewing lava 
tuesday afternoon about 175 people in the village of el caracol and 
80 from el patrocinio cleared out of their homes late wednesday 
hours ahead of a small river of lava that destroyed their 
coffeebean fields 
but a number of farmers in other villages in the area stayed 
behind sanchez said he said the lava is flowing down pacayas 
slopes in a southeasterly direction at about 15 feet an hour 
the 8421foot peak one of 32 volcanos dotting guatemala has 
been erupting intermittently since it first turned active jan 21 
1987 on tuesday the volcano blew open a new crater 
the pacaya continues active spewing out lava with constant 
explosions sanchez said 
in nicaragua santiago volcano 12 miles southeast of the 
capital managua began releasing white gases on sunday but 
scientists monitoring the activity say there is no immediate danger 
of an eruption 
santiago is one of three in the masaya complex one of the most 
active volcanic ranges in central america its single crater has 
been releasing gases about once every two decades 
lava flows often have followed the initial eruptions but they 
solidified before reaching populated areas 
favio segura an engineer with the nicaraguan institute of 
territorial studies told reporters it is difficult to predict if 
santiago will develop a large or small lava flow 
he said three nicaraguan and three british vulcanologists are 
monitoring the peak around the clock 
the national association of geologists has reported no 
immediate risk of a violent explosion that would endanger 
surrounding communities 
</TEXT>
