regularly on lenin square in downtown yerevan the armenian capital 
on one recent afternoon gena agabekyan and 100 other refugees 
complained outside the state agriculture committee offices that the 
government was refusing to give them jobs or homes 
agabekyan 50 said he was left without a job when he was fired 
as a crane operator for the staterun azerbaijan film committee in 
baku because i am an armenian 
even government officials who usually claim that interethnic 
brotherhood prevails in the soviet union acknowledge that the 
hostility felt by the neighboring caucasus peoples for each other 
was behind the refugee wave 
people were driven out only because they were of different 
nationality arkady volsky the head of a new governing committee 
in nagornokarabakh told the defense newspaper krasnaya zvezda 
yerevan a city of 12 million people has become a magnet for 
both refugees and people made homeless by the earthquake 
the armenian land use institute has set up a refugee placement 
center in the city its deputy director telemak mutafyan said 
there is no shortage of jobs or housing in armenia but many refugees 
are not willing to adjust to new conditions 
azerbaijanis left rural areas here and armenians come to us 
from baku and kirovabad and other azerbaijani cities mutafyan 
said a city man adjusts with great difficulty to a village 
many refugees are staying with relatives in yerevan but others 
have settled on their own in buildings condemned as unsafe 
according to mutafyan 
ironically the earthquake may have a silver lining for some 
refugees the kremlin has ordered that the devastated area be 
rebuilt in two years and thousands of construction workers are 
needed 
