despite last summers disastrous 
drought tractor dealer chuck german says the us agricultural 
economy is poised for recovery and growth thanks to lessons learned 
in the decadelong crisis that gripped the farm belt 
but german doubts manufacturers bullish forecasts for strong 
sales of tractors combines and farm implements he doesnt see a 
quick fix but a gradual improvement largely dependent upon 
cooperation from mother nature 
german 52 is president of german implement co of princeville 
a community of 1700 about 20 miles north of peoria his experiences 
the past 10 years are common among people who sell tractors 
our last good year was 1979 german said things started 
going downhill in 1980 and they really hit a low ebb in 1984 our 
volume that year was half of our 1979 volume 
in 1981 german laid off 25 percent of his employees 
indefinitely saying its sad but its been a matter of survival 
and waiting for things to pick back up 
like most experts german thought the farming industry was ripe 
for recovery last spring as tractor and combine sales started 
picking up but sales eased quickly in the drought that parched the 
midwest 
instead german watched the drought claim three neighborhing farm 
equipment dealers illinois has lost 1500 dealers since 1949 
according to the illinois retail farm equipment association 
german survived but had to cut expenses again just as he did at 
the start of the decade when the farm economy soured 
now german said his manufacturers ford motor co and japans 
kubota ltd are telling him to expect big demand in 1989 
