<TEXT>
after months of nothing but sunshine and 
blue skies rains finally are falling on italys parched croplands 
some areas had not seen rain in 80 days in others the rainfall 
in the last five months was less than half the average 
but the new rains may be too late it will take months to 
determine what the drought has done to the wheat crop fruit and 
olive orchards vineyards citrus groves and vegetable farms 
italians already know it will mean higher prices for some foods 
and possibly even for their bottle of wine however they may be 
saved higher costs for their pasta which is made from durum wheat 
while until a month ago we were very concerned about the 
effects of the drought on the recent harvest the recent rains have 
pretty much calmed our fears said albino ganapini a spokesman 
for barilla italys largest pasta producer if the rainy season 
continues normally as meteorologists are predicting then we will 
have a normal harvest 
he said the planting had been increased by 4 percent this year 
and noted that italy normally imports about 25 percent of the wheat 
it uses for pasta anyway 
but farm groups say the drought will mean higher prices for 
fruits and vegetables producers say the retail price of artichokes 
one of the most popular italian vegetables could triple from the 
current average price of 900 lire 67 cents apiece 
growers say fruit olive and citrus trees will produce less this 
year because of the drought which also is expected to diminish the 
grape harvest bringing the prospect of higher prices for wine 
