people living in families that dont conform to the ageold 
concept of mom dad and the kids are locked in battles in a number 
of communities where personal freedom is pitted against the desire 
to control who lives next door 
in some of denvers most exclusive neighborhoods for example 
unmarried people cant legally live together under a living in 
sin zoning code in poughkeepsie ny four or more people cant 
live in the same rental dwelling if theyre not of the same family 
and in chicago eight couples in a public housing project got 
married late last year to avoid eviction 
many communities have laws restricting housing according to 
varying definitions of what constitutes a family the reasons range 
from preserving quality of life in the face of an influx of 
outsiders to cutting backlogs of people waiting to get into public 
housing to fighting drugs 
supporters of denvers 30yearold code say it encourages strong 
familyoriented neighborhoods we should stand up and say we stand 
for families and traditional values said city councilman ted 
hackworth 
i just do not think its appropriate for the city to regulate 
whether you are married any more than we should regulate whether you 
go to church said councilwoman cathy reynolds who has fought for 
13 years to repeal the law 
elinor lewallen whose neighborhood is covered by the ordinance 
said she opposed it because if her husband were to die she would be 
barred from seeking a livein companion so she could continue living 
in her home 
the city council is scheduled to vote on the matter march 27 
poughkeepsie in its ordinance passed last month to keep college 
students from overcrowding apartments defined family as a group 
which in theory size appearance structure and function 
resembles a traditional family unit cooking together and sharing 
expenses 
the local newspapers got it a little confused they said it 
meant that kate and allie wouldnt be able to live together but 
thats not right said city clerk patricia havens kate and 
allie is a cbstv show in which two divorced women and their three 
children share an apartment 
delray beach fla approved an ordinance last august allowing 
only one person outside of the immediate family defined as 
parents and children to live with a family in a singlefamily 
home city officials say it is meant to curb overcrowding that can 
lead to increased garbage and noise traffic congestion and health 
and safety problems in neighborhoods 
as of last month officials had cited 11 homes all owned by 
haitians 
the american civil liberties union of florida is deciding on a 
challenge said attorney jim k green of the palm beach county 
