<TEXT>
a jury has awarded 36 fired casino workers 388 
million in a case that could affect the way nevadas gaming industry 
hires and fires its employees 
the federal court jury on thursday found the las vegas hilton 
guilty of age and sex discrimination breach of contract bad faith 
and inflicting severe emotional distress in the firing of the 
workers in september 1983 
hilton attorneys contended that casinos have the right to hire 
and fire at will because of the volatile nature of the business and 
the large amount of cash that is handled 
the resort also claimed the dealers understood they could be 
fired at will and accepted it as a tradeoff for large amount of 
money they made in wages and tips 
the dealers though claimed they were the victims of age and sex 
discrimination when they were replaced by younger female workers 
and contended the hotel gave them an implied contract when hired 
that they would not be fired except with justifiable cause 
casinos have traditionally held themselves to be above the 
law said brian berman an attorney for the plaintiffs we think 
the jury sent a clear example to the employers in the state of 
nevada that they cannot do this 
hilton executives testified that the workers were fired over the 
1983 labor day weekend after other unsuccessful attempts to clear 
up an unusually low win percentage in the hotels blackjack pit 
the verdict came after four days of deliberation following a 
14week trial 
the biggest portion of the award was for punitive damages which 
the jury assessed at 30 million 
steve wynn owner of the golden nugget hotel and casino attacked 
the verdict saying it was stupid for a jury to award that much in 
such a case 
the affected dealers disagreed 
its been 5 years of praying and a little hope said jack 
bosarge we realized we were up against one of the biggest 
corporations in the world but we all stuck together and came out on 
top 
hilton attorneys said they would ask the verdict be set aside 
claiming the jury was misled by sympathy for the workers if that 
fails resort attorneys said they would appeal 
were very disappointed said hilton attorney raymond kelly 
casino manager robert kelley and the hilton did exactly what it 
had to do under the circumstances 
all but five of the casino workers won claims for age 
discrimination and were awarded sums ranging from 7000 to 107000 
for lost wages each plaintiff also was given 200000 for the 
