selfimposed friday midnight deadline indefinitely until he rules 
on whether it is legal for railroad workers to strike in sympathy 
with airlines workers 
patterson gave no indication how long the temporary restraining 
order would remain in effect or when he would issue a written 
opinion on the complex labor dispute 
his secretary kathleen howley said patterson on friday decided 
to extend the deadline because the transcript of two days of 
hearings he conducted was not immediately available and electrical 
power in manhattans federal courthouse would be off for several 
hours on saturday for testing purposes 
i hope to render an opinion as soon as possible patterson 
told lawyers for both sides at the end of the second day of hearings 
on thursday but gave no indication when that might be 
less than an hour after strikebound eastern filed for chapter 11 
protection from creditors patterson heard competing legal arguments 
from lawyers for four metropolitan area railroads and the unions 
that represent their workers 
the unions claim that federal law allows secondary picketing in 
the railroad and airline industries 
but the railroads maintain that the law requires their employees 
to stay on the job until they go through a series of mandated 
arbitration steps 
