<TEXT>
a microsoft corp shareholder has filed a federal 
classaction lawsuit alleging the computer software publisher and 
two of its officers violated us securities laws by misleading 
stockholders about the companys financial outlook 
microsoft shareholders were damaged when the price of the stock 
plummeted 137 percent tuesday after microsoft announced it faced 
lowerthanexpected thirdquarter sales and profits according to 
allegations in the suit filed in us district court in seattle by 
bruce adelstein 
the suit says microsoft gave no indication in the weeks before 
the announcement that it was facing any problems it seeks 
undetermined compensatory and punitive damages 
we are reviewing the plaintiffs claims and we believe them to 
be entirely without merit william h neukom microsoft vice 
president of law and corporate affairs said in a news release 
friday microsoft intends to defend the case vigorously the case 
is now before the courts and microsoft will not offer comment 
outside of this statement 
in addition to microsoft the suit names as plaintiffs jon a 
shirley microsoft president and chief operating officer and 
francis j gaudette the companys vice president treasurer and 
chief financial officer microsoft cofounder and chairman bill 
gates is not listed as a defendant 
microsofts stock traded over the counter dropped by 850 a 
share to 5350 tuesday after the company announced it expected 
lower profits and sales for its third quarter ending march 31st it 
would be the first time quarterly profits declined since the company 
went public three years ago 
microsoft blamed the lower forecast on delays in shipping new 
versions of its wordprocessing software microsoft word and 
overstocking by key distributors 
microsoft predicted thirdquarter sales at 180 million to 200 
million down from the 200 million to 215 million expected by many 
market analysts 
the company had sales of 1618 million and profits of 373 
million in the third quarter of last year it said it expected 
profits for the current quarter to be somewhat less than a year 
ago 
adelsteins seattle attorney steven berman said the suit 
alleges that in a quarterly report filed feb 10 with the securities 
and exchange commission and in conferences with investors and 
analysts that month microsoft and its executives gave no indication 
of the inventory problems or that shipments of the new word versions 
would be delayed 
the suit says that as a direct result of the companys belated 
disclosures of the problems tuesday the markets response to 
microsofts announcement was swift and severe 
it alleges the microsoft officers misled stockholders to protect 
their jobs enhance the value of their microsoft stock and holdings 
and cover up their own prior misconduct and mismangement of 
microsoft and avoid being held responsible 
the class named in the suit covers investors who bought microsoft 
stock between jan 19 and march 6 berman said he didnt know how 
many people that covered although 19 million shares of microsoft 
were traded during that period 
adelstein bought 1400 shares of microsoft on feb 10 when the 
stock closed at 63 a share berman said 
