<TEXT>
unemployment dropped to a 15year low of 51 
percent in february as employers created 289000 jobs the 
government said friday in a report cited as evidence of surprising 
sustained vigor in the economy 
wall street seemed to regard the growth as too vigorous as stock 
prices fell on the labor departments announcement analysts cited 
concerns the federal reserve board may raise interest rates to cool 
down the economy as employers bid up wage rates in an 
evertightening labor market 
a record 629 percent of the workingage population was at work 
last month matching the high set in january the department said in 
data calculated from its monthly household survey 
the jobless rate stuck at 53 percent or 54 percent for five 
months fell 03 percentage point in february to 51 percent its 
lowest since may 1974 the last time the rate was lower was in 
december 1973 when it hit 49 percent 
the gain of 289000 nonfarm jobs in february reflected improved 
conditions in serviceproducing industries such as health care and 
retail trade according to a separate survey of business payrolls 
februarys job gains although strong were off from januarys 
huge increase of 415000 jobs last months harsh weather cut 22000 
jobs from construction employment manufacturing jobs were down 
8000 after rising steadily since september 
those decreases were more than made up for by a gain of 321000 
jobs in the service sector of the economy including gains in health 
and business services and in retail trade 
many analysts had been expecting unemployment to be stagnant or 
little changed last month developments wall street would have taken 
as a sign the economic expansion was slowing down 
wall street is concerned because the economy has shown few signs 
of flagging despite a yearlong campaign by the federal reserve to 
dampen growth and restrain inflation by pushing up interest rates 
after fridays report some analysts expect further credit 
tightening 
any way you look at it this is more strength than the feds 
going to tolerate and that means interest rates will be heading 
up said economist david wyss of data resources inc in lexington 
mass 
daniel t van dyke senior economist at bank of america in san 
francisco commented were adding jobs much faster than the labor 
force is growing the report portends more monetary tightening 
just last month alan greenspan the chairman of the federal 
reserve said he had found recent price gains disturbing and 
laid part of the blame on an acceleration in wage increases 
februarys report however showed that seasonally adjusted 
average hourly earnings were up just 01 percent while average 
weekly earnings declined 02 percent both categories had posted 
strong gains during january 
economist michael evans head of a washington consulting firm 
saw some underlying signs of economic weakness in the report 
including the drop in manufacturing employment a shortening of the 
average work week and steady overtime hours at factories 
i read this report as saying the economy is slowing down even 
though the socalled headline figures give the veneer of strength 
evans said 
that interpretation was disputed by jerry jasinowski chief 
economist of the national association of manufacturers who said 
manufacturing was strong except for autos 
virtually all of manufacturing continues to report good orders 
and pretty strong production he said all i get is reports 
about how strong orders and the economy are overall 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater called the drop in the 
unemployment rate good news 
jobs are still the best barometer of a sound economy he 
said while the numbers are volatile on a monthly basis the 
economy can continue to create jobs and inflation remain in check 
overall the civilian labor force contracted by 247000 people 
last month to 1232 million while 142000 workers found jobs 
the commissioner of the labor statistics janet l norwood told 
congress that most of last months jobless decrease was among young 
adults and hispanics groups whose jobless rates tend to be erratic 
the jobless rate among whites was 43 percent down from 46 
percent in january while for blacks it was 119 percent down from 
12 percent 
the jobless rate for hispanics plunged to 68 percent from 84 
percent in january 
the rate for teenagers dropped by 16 percentage points to 148 
percent while the unemployment rate for young adults aged 20 to 24 
fell 12 points to 81 percent 
